944001	1025090		Callicebus (Torquatus) Goodman et al., 1998	Goodman et al., 1998	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Pitheciidae	Cheracebus				subgenus	synonym	2017-03-30		944001		S.N. Alexander, ITIS Data Development Specialist: 'Groves listed Torquatus as a subgenus of Callicebus Thomas, 1903, with Callicebus torquatus (Hoffmannsegg, 1807), as the type species. As pointed out by Groves himself (in litt.), Goodman et al.'s suggestion of the name Torquatus, as proposed, does not conform to the requirements of Article 13 of the ICZN (1999): Names published after 1930. 13.1. 'To be available, every new name published after 1930 must satisfy the provisions of Article 11 and must - 13.1.1 be accompanied by a description or definition that states in words characters that are purported to differentiate the taxon, or - 13.1.2 be accompanied by a bibliographic reference to such a public statement [...], or - 13.1.3 be proposed expressly as a new replacement name (nomen novum) for an available name [...]'. Thus the name Torquatus is a nomen nudum, and unavailable.' (Byrne et al., 2016)	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Pitheciidae|Callicebinae

944052	1147540		Lepilemur wrightae Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates	Lemuroidea	Lepilemuridae	Lepilemur		wrightae		species	homotypicSynonym	2021-03-29		944052		Mittermeier, Russell A., Anthony B. Rylands, and Don E. Wilson, eds. (2013): Status:  CITES - Appendix I; IUCN - Critically Endangered.David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named 'in honor of Dr. Patricia Wright', and originally given as 'Lepilemur wrighti', which SHOULD have been 'wrightae', but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lemuriformes|Lemuroidea|Lepilemuridae|Lepilemur

944062	1147550		Lepilemur grewcockorum Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates	Lemuroidea	Lepilemuridae	Lepilemur		grewcockorum		species	homotypicSynonym	2021-03-29		944062		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named 'in honor of Bill and Berniece Grewcock', and originally given as 'Lepilemur grewcocki', which SHOULD have been 'grewcockorum', but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -orum appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lemuriformes|Lemuroidea|Lepilemuridae|Lepilemur

944094	572900		Galagoides demidovii (G. Fischer, 1808)	(G. Fischer, 1808)	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Galagidae	Galagoides		demidovii		species	homotypicSynonym	2017-03-30		944094		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: The specific epithet has caused considerable confusion. The name as it originally appeared [demidoff] is accompanied by a description and thus fulfills the criteria of availability. Subsequent workers cast doubt on the validity of the name, preferring to accept G. demidovii Fischer, 1808, or emending the spelling of the 1806 name. Schwartz (1931b) maintained that the name was not latinized, however, according to Article 31 of the ICZN, it must be treated as a noun in apposition to the generic name, and is therefore acceptable (Jenkins, 1987:98). Rylands (pers. comm. 26 June 2014) considered the matter and agreed to follow Jenkins (1987) and Groves (2001) in using the epithet as originally published, and treating the emendation as unjustified	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lorisiformes|Galagidae|Galagoides

(1989) recognized G. thomasi Elliot, 1907, as a full species, partially sympatric with demidoff; followed by Groves (2001c), who considered that a number of other species would eventually be recognized in addition. 944764	944150		Cebus xanthocephalus Spix, 1823	Spix, 1823	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Cebidae	Cebus		xanthocephalus		species	synonym	2021-03-29		944764		S.N. Alexander, ITIS Data Development Specialist: Groves (2001) treats xanthocephalus as a junior synonym of nigritus. Anthony Rylands (pers. comm., 24 January 2021) notes that xanthocephalus has a rust-colored chest and no black on the head, while Spix (1823) mentions Wied's xanthosternos as having a yellow chest and black 'points' on the head, and nigritus does not have a rust-colored chest. Rylands also notes that Spix places xanthocephalus in the forests of Rio de Janeiro, while the southern limit to xanthosternos is the Rio Jequitinhonha on the border of Bahia and Minas Gerais, and nigritus occurs south of the Rio Doce in Rio de Janeiro. As the putative gegraphic distribution of xanthocephalus corresponds to nigritus, but the appearance does not, Rylands views xanthocephalus as a nomen dubium	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Cebidae|Cebinae|Sapajus

(2005): Comments:  Not a subspecies of C. satanas (Bonvicino et al., 2003b).Wilson & Reeder, eds. (2005): Status:  CITES - Appendix II; IUCN - Vulnerable as C. satanus utahickae.David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named for the curator 'Fräulein Uta Hick', who is also referred to as 'Miss Hick', and originally given as 'utahicki', which SHOULD have been 'utahickae', but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Pitheciidae|Pitheciinae|Chiropotes

Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. Alexander, ITIS Data Development Specialist: When von Humboldt published the epithet for Humboldt's Woolly Monkey he spelled the epithet both as lagotricha and as lagothricha, a lapsus on his part. While it can be argued that 'lagotricha' includes an incorrect Latinization of the Greek word meaning 'hair', the first subsequent revision of the genus (Fooden, 1963) used the spelling 'lagothricha', thus 'lagothricha' is correct under the Zoological Code	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Atelidae|Atelinae|Lagothrix

Alexander, ITIS Data Development Specialist: 'Adopting the Phylogenetic Species Concept, Gippoliti (2017) suggested that baumstarki Matschie, 1905, and pyrrhonotus (Hemprich and Erhenberg, 1829) should be treated as full species, with pyrrhonotus having two subspecies, the nominate form and also the white-nosed formosus Elliot, 1909, with a narrow horizontal black band from the eye to the ear; this latter from southwest Ethiopia, Uganda, and presumably the south east of South Sudan. Erythrocebus baumstarki and E. p. patas in this arrangement have black faces and noses, whereas E. pyrrhonotus has a white nose. Yvonne de Jong and Thomas M. Butynski (in litt. to Russell A. Mittermeier, 17 January 2020) also argued that baumstarki should be 'a full species based on its geographic isolation (>180 km to the nearest other population [pyrrhonotus in Laikipia to the north ... separated by a forest barrier]) and its distinct phenotype (e.g., black nose, lack of white moustache, and dark grey upper limbs, whereas pyrrhonotus has a white nose, white moustache, and lacks dark grey on the upper hind legs).'' (Anthony Rylands, pers. comm., 20 December 2020)	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Cercopithecoidea|Cercopithecidae|Cercopithecinae|Cercopithecini|Erythrocebus

Subsequent workers cast doubt on the validity of the name, preferring to accept G. demidovii Fischer, 1808, or emending the spelling of the 1806 name. Schwartz (1931b) maintained that the name was not latinized, however, according to Article 31 of the ICZN, it must be treated as a noun in apposition to the generic name, and is therefore acceptable (Jenkins, 1987:98). Fischer, 1808)	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Galagidae	Galagoides		demidovii	demidovii	subspecies	synonym	2017-03-30		945074		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: The specific epithet has caused considerable confusion. The name as it originally appeared [demidoff] is accompanied by a description and thus fulfills the criteria of availability. Subsequent workers cast doubt on the validity of the name, preferring to accept G. demidovii Fischer, 1808, or emending the spelling of the 1806 name. Schwartz (1931b) maintained that the name was not latinized, however, according to Article 31 of the ICZN, it must be treated as a noun in apposition to the generic name, and is therefore acceptable (Jenkins, 1987:98). Rylands (pers. comm. 26 June 2014) considered the matter and agreed to follow Jenkins (1987) and Groves (2001) in using the epithet as originally published, and treating the emendation as unjustified	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lorisiformes|Galagidae|Galagoides|Galagoides demidoff

Fischer, 1806)	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Galagidae	Galagoides		demidoff	demidoff	subspecies	valid	2021-03-29		945737		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: The specific epithet has caused considerable confusion. The name as it originally appeared [demidoff] is accompanied by a description and thus fulfills the criteria of availability. Subsequent workers cast doubt on the validity of the name, preferring to accept G. demidovii Fischer, 1808, or emending the spelling of the 1806 name. Schwartz (1931b) maintained that the name was not latinized, however, according to Article 31 of the ICZN, it must be treated as a noun in apposition to the generic name, and is therefore acceptable (Jenkins, 1987:98). Rylands (pers. comm. 26 June 2014) considered the matter and agreed to follow Jenkins (1987) and Groves (2001) in using the epithet as originally published, and treating the emendation as unjustified	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lorisiformes|Galagidae|Galagoides|Galagoides demidoff

572900		572803	Galagoides demidoff (G. Fischer, 1806)	(G. Fischer, 1806)	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Galagidae	Galagoides		demidoff		species	valid	2021-03-29		572900		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: The specific epithet has caused considerable confusion. The name as it originally appeared [demidoff] is accompanied by a description and thus fulfills the criteria of availability. Subsequent workers cast doubt on the validity of the name, preferring to accept G. demidovii Fischer, 1808, or emending the spelling of the 1806 name. Schwartz (1931b) maintained that the name was not latinized, however, according to Article 31 of the ICZN, it must be treated as a noun in apposition to the generic name, and is therefore acceptable (Jenkins, 1987:98). Rylands (pers. comm. 26 June 2014) considered the matter and agreed to follow Jenkins (1987) and Groves (2001) in using the epithet as originally published, and treating the emendation as unjustified	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lorisiformes|Galagidae|Galagoides

The form of the name is changed in accordance with the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature, Art. 31.1.2 (International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature, 1999).Wilson & Reeder, eds. (2005): Status:  CITES - Appendix II; IUCN - Lower Risk (lc).David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named for Nancy Ma, and originally given as 'nancymai', which SHOULD have been 'nancymaae' (or 'nancymae,' depending on the specifics of Latinization used), but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Aotidae|Aotus

Alexander, ITIS Data Development Specialist: 'In her ongoing studies on the taxonomy and distributions of patas monkeys, Yvonne de Jong (in litt. to Anthony B., Rylands, 19 January 2020) considered that further research is needed regarding the taxonomic status of pyrrhonotus. It appears, for example, that it occurs in a cline with patas monkeys in Central Africa and she indicated that it would be appropriate to leave it as a subspecies of E. patas for the time being.  Gippoliti's 2017 review was only partial and, considering the little-known and numerous synonyms (see Groves, 2001), further research on patas monkeys throughout their range is urgently needed, especially since some 'forgotten' but valid taxa might well be endangered.' 1147534		572811	Aotus nancymai Hershkovitz, 1983	Hershkovitz, 1983	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates		Aotidae	Aotus		nancymai		species	valid	2021-03-29		1147534		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named for Nancy Ma, and originally given as 'nancymai', which SHOULD have been 'nancymaae' (or 'nancymae,' depending on the specifics of Latinization used), but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Haplorrhini|Simiiformes|Aotidae|Aotus

1147540		572792	Lepilemur wrighti Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Louis Jr., Engberg, Lei, Geng, Sommer, Randriamampionona, Randriamanana, Zaonarivelo et al., 2006	Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Primates	Lemuroidea	Lepilemuridae	Lepilemur		wrighti		species	valid	2021-03-29	Louis, Edward E. Jr., Shannon E. Engberg, Runhua Lei, Huimin Geng, Julie A. Sommer, et al. 2006-09-01. Molecular and Morphological Analysis of the Sportive Lemurs (Family Megaladapidae: Genus Lepilemur) Reveals 11 Previously Unrecognized Species. Museum of Texas Tech Special Publications, no. 49. 1-47. 0169-0237. Available online at https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/55017363.	1147540		David Nicolson - ITIS Data Development Coordinator: Named 'in honor of Dr. Patricia Wright', and originally given as 'Lepilemur wrighti', which SHOULD have been 'wrightae', but this does not appear to be a correctable error under the ICZN Art. 32.2 and 32.5. Use of -i instead of -ae appears to be an incorrect Latinization, which is not to be considered an inadvertent error (Art. 32.5.1), so the error is not one that 'must' be corrected, and it must be considered the 'correct original spelling.' In a discussion on the ICZN-List (March 2021) it was generally agreed that there is a problem for cases where a name was incorrectly formed/Latinized under Art. 31.1.2 (incorrect use of ending -i/-orum/-ae/-arum, according to the number & sex of honorees) of the 4th edition (1999) of the Code, in that the Article doesn't contain a corrective option, and the wording of Article 32 does not include this type of correction. This 'glitch' will be addressed in the next edition of the Code, but until this is resolved, ITIS will make note of these cases and try to follow current usage, where possible	Animalia|Bilateria|Deuterostomia|Chordata|Vertebrata|Gnathostomata|Tetrapoda|Mammalia|Theria|Eutheria|Primates|Strepsirrhini|Lemuriformes|Lemuroidea|Lepilemuridae|Lepilemur
